Together with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social programme.
The architects are so much easier to put under a hat their demanding profession and child care.
The Mini Kindergarten is an original idea of Arch.Design's employees and with the support of management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The Executive Mini Kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operation Programme from the resources of the European Social Fund and from the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (subsidies amounting to CZK 2, 8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment were obtained and for a period of 2 years qualified staff and operations were provided.
After spending the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to operate the Mini Kindergarten 3 for further years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took place for a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are cared for by fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but the day over several children changes.
Kindergarten management is flexible to meet the needs of parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of kindergarten - without regard to the corporate hierarchy and their respective positions.
Although it is individual education and care, the content of the programme in the Mini Kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children are not only playing here, especially they are given excellent instruction - from basic knowledge to preschool education, by the way, they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can at any time take a look at the children and thus avoid the stress of late picking up the children from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder there are natural and loyal employer-employee relationships here.
Arch.Design thus became one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, who are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Look at Gaudi's interiors
The roof is like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are cracked fish mules.
This is Casa Batlló from Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house was nicknamed "Knochenhaus" with its organic forms.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splits and mosaics, the reflective facades and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and beings.
Only when we look at it more closely can we see that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the whole facade is still plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and entangled shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even holes and lashes.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the rebuilding of a house dating back to 1877, which the architect Emilio Sala Cortese performed.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally stood on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló rental house alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the reality and also the use of mosaics on the façade were created on his desk.
However, numerous other artists and sculptors also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's House Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "accommodating house".
It is also said that on the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the Patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilating channels and typical fireplaces for the time being.
It's a bit bizarre that their 45-degree slope is already on.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and could not be deceived by them at all.
Before the construction began, he obtained from the city the corresponding building permit, but the information he made on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they asked for help.
The Councillors also encountered, among other things, the fact that construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the request of the district in question, Josep Batlló submitted a request for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was granted to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Through the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could chat comfortably, without having to refrain from some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house also received a rather unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudí's renovation besides a new façade.
Also impressive is Gaudí's game with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts.
The play of these two colors gives all the floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló house, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The owners of the house only decided in the year on this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were maintained, and they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the building monument is not a paparazzi, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist licenses get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Those who want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the home dwellers and visit him at home.
