A longer index finger than a ring finger reduces the risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and this is particularly true in men up to sixty," explained the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors exist, such as family health stress, added Mrs Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the right hand index finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the probability of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of the men whose ring and index fingers were the same.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty-seven even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research revealed that the testosterone is precisely accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that he knew this study fleetingly, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to be "fully proven".
