Two facts are particularly evident in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
Secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy supporters rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the strong break-in last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, reducing the regional average (see Graph 2).
About 44% of respondents said that they are satisfied with the democratic practice of their country. That is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a marked increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined its efforts for more democracy.
This continued even during the world economic crisis, possibly because Latin America's countries experienced only a short recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up in a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
But there are strong mood differences from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the beginning of the survey do many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country a greater problem than in unemployment (see Graph 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: around 71% of respondents over-regionally indicated that the private sector is indispensable for development, with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
