Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA's Astrobiological Institute, which conducted the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes, which are both exposed, may be able to replace one element by the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to chemical behaviour similar to that of phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it almost all lubricates," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life-form can occur naturally, either on earth or on another planet or moon, on which the arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new. But so far there has not been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early years of the earth, she says, therefore science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early age of the earth," says Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and National Health.
