On the other hand, the Deputy Head of Government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the head of government, who had outwitted the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It was anticipated that Merkel's position was not an error in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on the design of our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the old traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, we are beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis in Germany.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German Mark - although it currently sounds more like Science Fiction - supports most of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reshaping of the euro according to German proposals. That means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that violate the rules; possibly the suspension of payments by some countries as well as the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has stood out for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the dissociation between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign set the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At that time this was strongly criticised. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion were absolutely against a rescue from Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel comes up with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be rescued while at the same time requiring private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has driven the Irish crisis and all the following.
But her proposal, albeit somewhat sweet, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It says to everyone that - although unpopular measures must be taken now - the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from that date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the countries in question will be severely penalised, forced to declare themselves incapacitated and, in this case, to take over part of the costs of the private sector.
Germany shows us that we need to take a strong growth rate, with high savings and investment rates, measurement of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as indicated by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we'd do a bad thing not to understand.
It is not just a matter of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has prepared his way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything would change about it.
Among the possibilities considered is that we should not exclude from the euro area that is fully packed with few serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and regulatory environment
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to avoid a penalty.
The alleged exclusion of two players from the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 game against the Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether or not it was an unportal act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will comply with the prescribed penalty at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules, but followed in this sport.
Part of the debate on the case presented is that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who in his hymn pretends to be noble and honoured and who on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether the conduct which is not expressly prohibited by the Statutes contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a regulatory circumvention. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to bypass its sense.
In this case, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, for it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid any unfair advantage from the opposing team on the part of the gamblers. This did not happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand under false play or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and accepted the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the intentional fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was neither brought into a more unfavourable position nor gained benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that its own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage obviously is that the players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, up to a certain degree, uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually leave as well. Moreover, with this approach, the players receive a penalty and go over to the second card cycle in which they leave with a card for card accumulation less than in the first cycle.
It is therefore not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to deal with the penalty (it would actually be a clear case of circumvention), they preferred to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing from a punishment.
Although the border between invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the polemics were created as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the kind of provoked transmission of rules.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
