The US is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves to the service bodies for visa applications prior to their conversation with the consulate, and costs will be reduced accordingly.
As from 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the Embassy of the United States and in consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application service bodies (ASC, the initial letters in English) prior to their consultation in the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the conversation.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of handling the visa is reduced, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is delivered.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the opposite is 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visas do not have to have a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
As biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation in the consulate remain there for less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo do not have to pay the service surcharge of 26 dollars.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
